Questions¶

Stated below are the set of questions which the report will aim to answer, as well as the broad steps taken to come to conclusions. Detailed steps are documented under each question heading.

Questions regarding popularity and profitability:¶

Are popularity and profitability postively correlated?

It could be easy to assume that the more popular a movie the hgiher the profitability, however it may be the case that popular movies simply have a higher budget without the corresponding revenues. Once it this relationship is establish we will investigate how columns in the database affect popularity and profitability.

1. Plot scatter graph of popularity vs profitability containing linear regression

Questions regarding popularity:¶

How do the average popularity scores of each genre compare? 

1. Create dataFrame containing mean popularity for each distinct genre
2. Sort dataFrame in descending order
3. Plot bar graph popularity by genre

How does release year affect popularity? 

1. Create dataFrame containing mean and median popularity for each release year
2. Plot line graph of mean and median popularity by release year

How does release year affect mean genre popularity? 

1. Create dataFrame containing mean popularity with release year/genre as column/index
2. Create line graph for each genre as subplots

How does run time affect popularity? 

1. Create dataFrame containing movie popularity and runtime
2. Plot scatter graph

Questions regarding profitability:¶

How do the number of genres affect profitability? 

1. Iterate through the columns listed above
2. Create dataFrame for each unique number of genres/cast members/production companies over each iteration
3. Create bar graph over each iteration

Which production companies are associated with the highest profiting movies? 

1. Create dataFrame containing 20 most profitable movies
2. Plot bar graph profitablity by production company

What is the most profitable movie of all time? 

1. Search dataFrame for most profitable movie

Data Wrangling¶

For further information of each of the fields used in this analysis follow this link:

https://developers.themoviedb.org/3/getting-started/introduction

Core Features of Interest¶

  1. id: TMDB movie id
  2. popularity: the popularity score given to a movie is a function of todays views and votes as well as the previous days populairty score. It is therefore a current popularity score rather than an all time popularity score.
  3. original_title: title of movie
  4. budget_adj: more useful comparison metric than budget for movies over many years
  5. revenue_adj: more useful comparison metric than budget for movies over many years
  6. cast: lead roles in move
  7. director: director(s) of movie
  8. runtime: run time of movie
  9. genres: genres of movie
  10. production_companies: production company associated with movie
  11. release_year Year: year of release

New Features Added¶

  1. profitabilty_adj = (revenue_adj - budget_adj): this feature gives an indicator of profitability, assuming budget is close to spend
  2. num_genres: number of genres associated with the movie
  3. num_production_companies: number of production companies associated with the movie
  4. num_directors: number of directors associated with the movie
  5. num_cast: number of cast members associated with the movie

Zero Values¶

In [1173]:
print('Number of zero valued budget rows: ' + str((df['budget_adj']==0).sum()))
print('Number of zero valued revenue rows: ' + str((df['revenue_adj']==0).sum()))

# repleace zero values with NaN so we can use replace na
df['budget_adj'] = df['budget_adj'].replace(0, np.NaN)
df['revenue_adj'] = df['revenue_adj'].replace(0, np.NaN)

Number of zero valued budget rows: 4615
Number of zero valued revenue rows: 4872

The data set is large so imputing NaN values with the mean/median/mode is not appropriate.

There are also a very large percentage of null values.

To calculate an estimate for zero values implement Linear Regression Model

After exploring the model, the most appropriate fields to calculate this linear regression are genres, runtime and release year.

In [1174]:
# define columns to be used in linear regression models
df_genres = df['genres'].str.get_dummies('|')
df_forLR = df[['runtime', 'release_year', 'budget_adj', 'revenue_adj']].merge(df_genres, left_index = True, right_index = True)
df_forLR.drop_duplicates()

budget_columns = df_genres.columns.tolist()
budget_columns.extend(['runtime', 'release_year', 'budget_adj'])

revenue_columns = df_genres.columns.tolist()
revenue_columns.extend(['runtime', 'release_year', 'revenue_adj'])
In [1175]:
# implement simple linear regression to predict zero values for NaN
budget_linreg = LinearRegression()

budget_data_with_null = df_forLR[budget_columns]

budget_data_without_null = budget_data_with_null.dropna()

train_budget_data_x = budget_data_without_null.iloc[:,:21]
train_budget_data_y = budget_data_without_null.iloc[:,21]

budget_linreg.fit(train_budget_data_x, train_budget_data_y)

budget_test_data = budget_data_with_null.iloc[:,:21]

budget_predicted = pd.Series(budget_linreg.predict(budget_test_data))

budget_predicted.index = df.index

# replace missing values
df['budget_adj'].fillna(budget_predicted, inplace = True)
In [1176]:
# implement simple linear regression to predict zero values for NaN
revenue_linreg  = LinearRegression()

revenue_data_with_null = df_forLR[revenue_columns]

revenue_data_without_null = revenue_data_with_null.dropna()

train_revenue_data_x = revenue_data_without_null.iloc[:,:21]
train_revenue_data_y = revenue_data_without_null.iloc[:,21]

revenue_linreg.fit(train_revenue_data_x, train_revenue_data_y)

revenue_test_data = revenue_data_with_null.iloc[:,:21]

revenue_predicted = pd.Series(revenue_linreg.predict(revenue_test_data))

revenue_predicted.index = df.index

# replace missing values
df['revenue_adj'].fillna(revenue_predicted, inplace = True)

Limitations¶

The biggest limitation of the data set was that there were many zero values for budget and revenue. It was a hard decision how to handle this as all solutions have their limitations. After exploring the data I decided release_year, runtime and genre were the best features to include within this linear regression, given their relationship with popularity and profitability. Using a measure of centre to approximate the zero values was not appropriate because of the size of the dataset and the number of missing values in relation to the size of the dataset (around 50%.) I think the next option was to simply remove these rows, to leave a smaller more accurate data set.

Another limitation of the data set was that many of the key fields that I was interested in analysing were listed in one column. For instance with 'Genre' there would be a list of genres associated with a movie in one column. This structure would make it impossible to analyse statistics based on individual genres. There are different ways in which the data could be structured. After experimenting with dataFrames which required for loops to create, I decided to utilise vector/matrix operations in numpy and pandas to achieve this as it made the code far more efficient to run.

The popularity feature provided is heavily weighted towards current popularity, rather than all time popularity. I think a more interesting analysis or complementary analaysis would be to look at all time popularity ratings.

  • This does not explain why a movie might be popular or profitable, simply that the higher the popularity the hgiher the profitability and visa verca.

How does release year affect popularity? ¶

  • The greater the release year the greater the popularity. This is true for both mean and median popularity, although median popularity tails off slightly in more recent years. Intuitively this makes sense as the popularity score is a current rating that is calculated based on user activity over the last two days, rather than an all time popularity rating.

  • Mean popularity is always higher than median popularity (skewed to right) which implies the movies with high popularity scores are dominant drawing the mean up.

  • In general, over a 5-10 year period mean popularity does not deviate more than 0.2 although there is a noticeable spike in mean popularity from 2013-2015. The next question looks at if this particular trend holds true for all genres.

  • The more current the release year the more movies TMDB have on record.

How does release year affect mean genre popularity? ¶

Conclusions

  • There is positive correlation between release year with most genres.

  • The pronouced spike in mean popularity between 2013-2015 is present in all genres except: Animation, Music, Mystery Horror, Documentary, TV Movie and Foreign.

How does run time affect popularity? ¶

  • All movies with a popularity rating of 5 and higher are in the 90-180 minute range
  • Movies below 60 minutes have low popularity
  • Movies over 200 minutes have low popularity

Questions regarding profitability:¶

How do the number of genres affect profitability? ¶

  • Movies that ecompass 3 or more genres are more profitable than those that encompass 1-2 genres.
  • Despite this fact, the vast majority of movies seem to encompass 1-3 genres, with fewer movies encompassing 4 and 5 genres.
